      <h1 class="display-4 fw-bold">How Much Money Will You Really Make in Investment Banking?</h1>
      <!--<p class="text-muted">December 10, 2024</p>-->
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Article Content -->
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-lg-8 mx-auto">
      <p class="lead">
        There are plenty of reasons you’ll rattle off in your investment banking interviews about why you want to enter the industry. Maybe you’re "fascinated by financial markets," "excited about the opportunity to work with CEOs," or "eager to support shareholder value." Some of these reasons might even be true.
      </p>
      <p class="lead">
        But let’s be honest—for the vast majority of people entering the field, a major motivation is money. Framing this as a desire to achieve financial freedom early in life, however, offers a more meaningful perspective. 
      </p>
        <p class="lead">
         With financial worries affecting millions across the U.S., the ability to achieve financial freedom is rare—achieving it early in life is even rarer. The amount of money needed depends on how you envision your lifestyle. While it’s unlikely you’ll be driving Lamborghinis or flying private jets by 30, you could have the freedom to choose a career based on passion rather than pay—or even decide not to work at all.
      </p>

     
      <p class="lead">
        Here’s a realistic look at the path to financial freedom, how it might play out depending on your career choices, and how it compares to other standard high-achieving career paths.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

