  <!-- Accordion: Investment Banking Career Paths -->
<div class="accordion mt-5" id="bankingPathsAccordion">
  <h2 class="fw-bold">Investment Banking Career Paths</h2>

  <!-- Example 1 -->
  <div class="accordion-item">
    <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingOne">
      <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseOne" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseOne">
        Example 1: Analyst → Private Equity → Business School
      </button>
    </h2>
    <div id="collapseOne" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="headingOne" data-bs-parent="#bankingPathsAccordion">
      <div class="accordion-body">
        <p>With a high salary and very little time to spend it, you should have a high savings rate of ~30% or even higher during the first few years of your career, leading to about ~$400K saved after four years of work. After about 4–5 years, you’ll have great exit opportunities, with many deciding to go to business school, transition to another area of finance, or enter a corporate role.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Years 1–2:</strong> $100k to $150K saved. </li>
          <li><strong>Years 3–4:</strong> Private Equity compensation $300k-$350k/year; $350 to $450K saved.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Considerations:</strong> This is a competitive path, both to break into investment banking and to enter private equity. The recruiting timelines are fast and early, and the transition from college autonomy to the demanding nature of investment banking can lead to burnout if you’re not prepared. Private equity can be incredibly lucrative and often offers better hours than banking, but culture, compensation, and career trajectories vary widely by firm. Research carefully before accepting a position in PE.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Example 2 -->
  <div class="accordion-item">
    <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingTwo">
      <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseTwo" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseTwo">
        Example 2: Analyst → Stay in Banking Through VP
      </button>
    </h2>
    <div id="collapseTwo" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingTwo" data-bs-parent="#bankingPathsAccordion">
      <div class="accordion-body">
        <p>Another common path is sticking with investment banking and climbing the ladder to VP. This requires grinding for at least six years (Analyst → Associate → VP), and the money ramps up quickly, with VPs at elite boutiques making mid-to-high six figures, and in rare cases, up to a million depending on the firm and the market.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Years 1–2:</strong> $100k to $150K saved. </li>
          <li><strong>Years 3–4:</strong> $250 to $350k compensation per year as you are promoted to Associate in year 3 or 4; $300 to $400K saved.</li>
          <li><strong>Years 5-6:</strong> $300k to $500k compensation per year; with the VP promotion coming in year 6 or 7.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Considerations:</strong> This path provides a direct route to financial freedom and is one of the most straightforward ways to become a millionaire by 30. However, the downside is that you will have limited exposure to other roles outside of investment banking, and the higher you rise (e.g., VP), the harder it is to make a significant career pivot. If you enjoy the work and are able to endure the grind, this can be an excellent path for the right person.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Example 3 -->
  <div class="accordion-item">
    <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingThree">
      <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseThree" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseThree">
        Example 3: MBA Associate
      </button>
    </h2>
    <div id="collapseThree" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingThree" data-bs-parent="#bankingPathsAccordion">
      <div class="accordion-body">
        <p>By entering the field as an MBA Associate, you get to skip the analyst years, earning more money upfront compared to analysts but entering the field with much less practical experience. Depending on your stage of life, your savings rate will vary widely, especially with student loan payments and family expenses.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Year 1:</strong> $250 to 350k/year; save $50k–$70k/year.</li>
          <li><strong>Years 2–4:</strong> $400 to $600k/year; with VP promotion coming between years 3 and 4.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Considerations:</strong> With prior work experience, you may have a better understanding of what corporate roles are like compared to younger analysts. However, MBA Associates often face narrower exit opportunities, so having clear goals before entering the field is crucial. This ensures you don’t settle for suboptimal exits due to burnout or a lack of direction.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

  <!-- Section: Comparing to Other Career Paths -->
  <div class="row mt-5">
    <div class="col-lg-8 mx-auto">
      <h2 class="fw-bold">How Does This Compare to Other Career Paths?</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Ok, that’s great and all, but how does this compare to other career paths? And with the stat that <strong>less than 1% of college graduates</strong> break into investment banking and <strong>top MBA programs placing only around 15%</strong> of their graduating classes into the field, if you can get into this competitive industry, you likely could enter other prestigious fields as well.
      </p>
      <p class="lead">
        What really matters is how investment banking stacks up against other <strong>high-paying, competitive career paths</strong>. Let’s go through a few common ones and weigh the pros and cons for different personality types, along with how the financial outcomes compare.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Accordion: Other Career Paths -->
<div class="accordion mt-4" id="otherPathsAccordion">
  <!-- Consulting -->
  <div class="accordion-item">
    <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingConsulting">
      <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseConsulting" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseConsulting">
        Consulting
      </button>
    </h2>
    <div id="collapseConsulting" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="headingConsulting" data-bs-parent="#otherPathsAccordion">
      <div class="accordion-body">
        <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Offers a better, but still not good, work-life balance compared to banking.</li>
          <li>Provides broad industry exposure and skill development that opens doors to various career paths, including leadership roles in corporate strategy or operations.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Slower financial growth due to lower starting salaries and bonuses compared to banking.</li>
          <li>Less opportunity to rapidly accumulate wealth and fewer chances to become a multi-millionaire early in your career.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Net Worth Potential:</strong> By age 30, consultants might accumulate $500K–$700K in net worth, significantly lower than if you stayed in banking.</p>
        <p><strong>Who Should Choose Consulting?</strong> This path is ideal for those who prioritize a better work-life balance, enjoy solving conceptual, rather than quantitative business problems, and value career flexibility. Consulting is also a good fit for those who plan to leverage their experience to transition into corporate leadership roles or entrepreneurial ventures.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Lawyer -->
  <div class="accordion-item">
    <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingLawyer">
      <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseLawyer" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseLawyer">
        Lawyer
      </button>
    </h2>
    <div id="collapseLawyer" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingLawyer" data-bs-parent="#otherPathsAccordion">
      <div class="accordion-body">
        <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>High earning potential for corporate and specialized lawyers, with top-tier partners earning $1M+ annually.</li>
          <li>Prestige and the ability to influence society or business through your work.</li>
          <li>Broad career flexibility, as legal expertise is valuable across industries.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Significant student debt and a grueling workload during law school and at the beginning of your career.</li>
          <li>Long hours, particularly at large firms, which may rival investment banking in intensity.</li>
          <li>Career progression to partnership or in-house roles can be uncertain and competitive.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Net Worth Potential:</strong> $500K–$1M+ by mid-30s for successful corporate lawyers, depending on career progression.</p>
        <p><strong>Who Should Choose Law?</strong> This is a great path for individuals who enjoy solving complex problems, have a strong interest in legal matters, and are willing to commit to the grind for a potentially lucrative career. It’s best suited for those seeking prestige and flexibility rather than rapid financial gains.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Doctor -->
  <div class="accordion-item">
    <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingDoctor">
      <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseDoctor" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseDoctor">
        Doctor
      </button>
    </h2>
    <div id="collapseDoctor" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingDoctor" data-bs-parent="#otherPathsAccordion">
      <div class="accordion-body">
        <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>High earning potential once fully established, with many specialists earning $300K–$500K+ annually.</li>
          <li>Job stability and demand for healthcare professionals are virtually guaranteed.</li>
          <li>Prestige and the satisfaction of helping others in a tangible way.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Significant upfront investment in time (4 years of med school + 3–7 years of residency/fellowship) and money, often leading to hundreds of thousands in student debt.</li>
          <li>Delayed income; most doctors don’t reach full earning potential until their mid-30s or later.</li>
          <li>Long hours and emotionally taxing work, especially in certain specialties.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Net Worth Potential:</strong> $1M+ is achievable by your mid-40s for high earners who manage their finances well.</p>
        <p><strong>Who Should Choose Medicine?</strong> This is the path for those passionate about healthcare and willing to sacrifice their 20s to build a fulfilling, impactful career. It’s not a fast track to financial freedom but offers stable, high long-term earning potential.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Software Engineer -->
  <div class="accordion-item">
    <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingEngineer">
      <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseEngineer" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseEngineer">
        Software Engineer
      </button>
    </h2>
    <div id="collapseEngineer" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingEngineer" data-bs-parent="#otherPathsAccordion">
      <div class="accordion-body">
        <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Strong earning potential with total compensation at top tech firms reaching $300K–$500K+ early in your career.</li>
          <li>Excellent work-life balance compared to many high-paying fields, with flexible hours and remote work options.</li>
          <li>High demand and transferable skills across industries.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Compensation growth can plateau in mid-level roles unless you transition to management or entrepreneurship.</li>
          <li>Job security depends on keeping skills up to date in a rapidly evolving industry.</li>
          <li>Fewer direct paths to financial freedom unless you pursue equity-heavy roles or startup ventures.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Net Worth Potential:</strong> $500K–$1M by your early-to-mid 30s for top performers at leading tech companies.</p>
        <p><strong>Who Should Choose Software Engineering?</strong> This is an ideal career for individuals who enjoy problem-solving, building products, and working in dynamic, tech-driven environments. It’s a great path for those who value flexibility and a balanced lifestyle over aggressive financial goals.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Going Directly to the Buy-Side -->
  <div class="accordion-item">
    <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingBuyside">
      <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseBuyside" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseBuyside">
        Going Directly to the Buyside
      </button>
    </h2>
    <div id="collapseBuyside" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingBuyside" data-bs-parent="#otherPathsAccordion">
      <div class="accordion-body">
        <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>High earning potential early on, with total compensation often exceeding $200K–$300K in your first year, and even more for successful associates or analysts.</li>
          <li>Exposure to investing from the start, with a clear path to leadership roles (e.g., portfolio manager).</li>
          <li>Greater career flexibility within finance, compared to investment banking.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Highly competitive entry, with limited spots for candidates without prior banking experience.</li>
          <li>Significant variability in firm culture and career trajectory, with many firms lacking strong training programs or well-defined career paths.</li>
          <li>Intense workload, particularly at private equity or hedge funds, though often less demanding than banking.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Net Worth Potential:</strong> $1M+ by early 30s for top performers at well-established buy-side firms.</p>
        <p><strong>Who Should Choose the Buy-Side?</strong> This path is best for individuals who are passionate about investing and want to maximize their financial potential early in their career. It’s an especially good fit for those who are confident in their abilities to perform under pressure in a competitive environment.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Corporate Roles -->
  <div class="accordion-item">
    <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingCorporate">
      <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseCorporate" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseCorporate">
        Corporate Role
      </button>
    </h2>
    <div id="collapseCorporate" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingCorporate" data-bs-parent="#otherPathsAccordion">
      <div class="accordion-body">
        <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Work-life balance is typically better than in banking or consulting, with more predictable hours.</li>
          <li>Lower stress levels and a more sustainable career path, especially in leadership roles.</li>
          <li>Opportunities for internal promotion and specialization within an industry.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Slower compensation growth, especially in the early years, compared to banking or consulting.</li>
          <li>Fewer opportunities to rapidly build wealth unless you climb to the C-suite or work in a highly lucrative sector.</li>
          <li>Career progression can be slower and dependent on company culture.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Net Worth Potential:</strong> $200K–$500K by age 30 for high performers, with significant upside potential later in leadership roles.</p>
        <p><strong>Who Should Choose a Corporate Role?</strong> This is a great path for those who value stability, are passionate about a specific industry, and want to develop deep expertise without the intense demands of consulting or banking. It’s ideal for individuals looking to balance financial success with a fulfilling personal life.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
